>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-5\">\n<p>  Climate Adapt. Floating and amphibious housing (2015).<a href=\"https://climate-adapt.eea.europa.eu/metadata/adaptation-options/floating-and-amphibious-housing/#ao_category\">https://climate-adapt.eea.europa.eu/metadata/adaptation-options/floating-and-amphibious-housing/#ao_category</a></p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-5\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-6\">\n<p>  Land8: Landscape Architects Network (2015). What is Amphibious Architecture and How Will it Help Cities Adapt to Climate Change? <a href=\"https://land8.com/what-is-amphibious-architecture-and-how-will-it-help-cities-adapt-to-climate-change/\">https://land8.com/what-is-amphibious-architecture-and-how-will-it-help-cities-adapt-to-climate-change/</a></p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-6\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-7\">\n<p>  Nilubon, P., Veerbeek, W., &#x26; Zevenbergen, C. (2016). Amphibious architecture and design: a catalyst of opportunistic adaptation? –case study Bangkok. Procedia-Social and Behavioral Sciences, 216, 470-480.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-7\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-8\">\n<p>  Figure 1. English et al. (2016). Thriving with water: Developments in amphibious architecture in north America. <a href=\"https://www.e3s-conferences.org/articles/e3sconf/pdf/2016/02/e3sconf_flood2016_13009.pdf\">https://www.e3s-conferences.org/articles/e3sconf/pdf/2016/02/e3sconf_flood2016_13009.pdf</a></p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-8\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-9\">\n<p>  Figure 2. Brears. R. (n.d). A Floating House to Resist the Floods of Climate Change\n.<a href=\"https://youngwaterleaders.thewaternetwork.com/article-FfV/a-floating-house-to-resist-the-floods-of-climate-change-zY8sRnPTmd2aqpyJrvinig\">https://youngwaterleaders.thewaternetwork.com/article-FfV/a-floating-house-to-resist-the-floods-of-climate-change-zY8sRnPTmd2aqpyJrvinig</a></p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-9\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-10\">\n<p>  Figure 3. Morphosis Team. (2009). FLOAT House. <a href=\"https://www.morphosis.com/architecture/126/\">https://www.morphosis.com/architecture/126/</a>.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-10\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-11\">\n<p>  Figure 4. Mangione, K. (2019). Figure 4. Noticed the blue cabin floating in False Creek? Here’s what it is. <a href=\"https://bc.ctvnews.ca/noticed-the-blue-cabin-floating-in-false-creek-here-s-what-it-is-1.4565356\">https://bc.ctvnews.ca/noticed-the-blue-cabin-floating-in-false-creek-here-s-what-it-is-1.4565356</a> —></p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-11\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","frontmatter":{"title":"Amphibious Buildings","strategyTypes":"Accommodate","date":"October 23, 2020","description":null,"tags":null}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"7ef71ed4-1390-5169-8364-90c50ce9086a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Amphibious Buildings"}}},{"node":{"id":"22c6ace5-a0f2-5bec-abaf-8db95e75a9fd","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/barrier-islands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Barrier Islands"}}},{"node":{"id":"ae5a1f35-fce3-53ea-84cb-05783ff86dca","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/beach-nourishment/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Beach Nourishment"}}},{"node":{"id":"6e12f862-8323-5f7a-991e-aee66741ab3d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/breakwaters/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Breakwaters"}}},{"node":{"id":"733c0edd-ab23-5a79-8b92-0a0a3fa66af0","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/coastal-wetlands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Coastal Wetlands"}}},{"node":{"id":"87e855d9-52ea-59bf-aedb-ccfe76a3df51","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-permits/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Permits"}}},{"node":{"id":"778be613-c456-5c81-b08b-d5515ae38ed9","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-transfers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Transfers"}}},{"node":{"id":"ea68ab98-acb3-5f86-bec1-7afa36349ca6","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dikes"}}},{"node":{"id":"8043b7a4-55d4-52a5-b9db-5b8a3e6c4bf6","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}}},{"node":{"id":"a8c82117-3f24-5832-ab8e-25826bf319e2","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dune-building-restoration/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dune Building / Restoration"}}},{"node":{"id":"0623976c-4c91-537d-a14b-2fc349d00999","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/easement-and-covenants/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Easement and Covenants"}}},{"node":{"id":"8a0c019c-f4f9-5197-be93-c8e22506f97b","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/emergency-planning-and-preparedness/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Emergency Planning Preparedness"}}},{"node":{"id":"1f64f01d-8737-5cfe-973b-fee09a2ac91a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/evacuation-routes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Evacuation Routes"}}},{"node":{"id":"f95c5798-23c9-5107-bc5b-41c0bee3130f","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/floodwalls/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"id":"2c782d6a-3e20-57d7-b88b-b28de7276c44","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/foreshore-tenure/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Foreshore Tenure"}}},{"node":{"id":"38db4e60-391a-5185-ac1d-505dffafd4ae","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"id":"1c92479b-69fb-5d6e-832f-715a1c4e6a13","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-acquisition/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Acquisition"}}},{"node":{"id":"11929fb9-bb5f-51fe-8be7-7725ae226fab","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-trust/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Trust"}}},{"node":{"id":"af206efc-f67c-5b26-a7d4-afefe2fc660c","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/protected-area-zoning/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Protected Area Zoning"}}},{"node":{"id":"1678f2e8-7dea-5a35-9e4f-7c258acc512d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"id":"f578c06a-426e-5ad3-9d4a-062a6cd6c531","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"id":"9886ab9a-0409-5f42-b606-4da1f6b5606d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"id":"e503d6cd-40ad-5238-9e81-3f1fd77d864a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"id":"35be0a4c-5325-585d-a143-1433d7cbd5b5","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"id":"b9524640-c924-53b8-a087-f5a144c3ad9d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Subdivision Regulation and Development Control"}}},{"node":{"id":"9d50eddd-7656-5a4d-b75b-5887ea8ad5be","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"id":"a6e87138-5a0d-5dc6-afe8-678a851a6028","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/amphibious-buildings/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Increases the value of real estate because of flood adaptation design</li>\n<li>Adaptable to variation in flood water levels <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></li>\n<li>Reduces the level of damage due to flooding       </li>\n<li>Amenable to soil subsistence and changes in sea level rise <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","challenges":"<ul>\n<li>Increases the cost for access to services such as sewage disposal, water supply, power, and gas, when compared to non-amphibious buildings <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></li>\n<li>Static elevated buildings are more vulnerable to the wind because elevation increases the effects of high wind speed on the building.</li>\n<li>Insurance companies may be reluctant to provide adequate coverage due to the increased risk of flood damage. </li>\n<li>Municipalities may be hesitant to issue permission for development approval</li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>FLOAT House</h3>\n<h4>New Orleans LA, USA</h4>\n<p>The Float House is a prototype for housing that adapts to coastal flooding. It is used in coastal areas that are susceptible to flooding. The design features an adaptable frame that acts as a raft. Guided steel masts allow the house to float up to as high as 12 feet.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> Not only does the float boat adapt to floods it also produces its own energy.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> The float boat project is a great example of sea-level rise adaptation through research and design. </p>","<h3>Floating Houses</h3>\n<h4>BC, Canada</h4>\n<p>Examples of floating houses or houseboats can be found in British Columbia along False Creek on Granville Island. These float houses are a landmark. Each house exhibits its own unique character. In the south of Richmond along the Fraser River, floating homes can also be found near Ladner and Queensborough. These little neighborhoods are examples of resiliency through water-based urbanism and embracing water as a culture. It should be noted, however, that because of planning regulations, it might be difficult to implement floating houses as an adaptation strategy at larger scales.</p>"],"images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 406px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/1217a5c615f191003a4ccf0f1d04b0d5/e33ef/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.5615763546798%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/1217a5c615f191003a4ccf0f1d04b0d5/e33ef/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/1217a5c615f191003a4ccf0f1d04b0d5/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/1217a5c615f191003a4ccf0f1d04b0d5/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/1217a5c615f191003a4ccf0f1d04b0d5/e33ef/Figure1.png 406w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 406px) 100vw, 406px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nElevated house in Galveston Texas <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup>  </p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 506px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c4aa63471de7b9e565f988710ddf6167/29f4e/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 49.80237154150198%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c4aa63471de7b9e565f988710ddf6167/29f4e/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c4aa63471de7b9e565f988710ddf6167/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/c4aa63471de7b9e565f988710ddf6167/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/c4aa63471de7b9e565f988710ddf6167/29f4e/Figure2.png 506w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 506px) 100vw, 506px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nA floating house <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 458px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/8c73f395c5a30285e5b66c57b84423ee/f7a31/Figure4.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.895196506550214%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/8c73f395c5a30285e5b66c57b84423ee/f7a31/Figure4.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/8c73f395c5a30285e5b66c57b84423ee/12f09/Figure4.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/8c73f395c5a30285e5b66c57b84423ee/e4a3f/Figure4.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/8c73f395c5a30285e5b66c57b84423ee/f7a31/Figure4.png 458w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 458px) 100vw, 458px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nFloating cabin; False Creek British Columbia <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 575px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/ac18e920778116dbd02a6c47eacef644/59415/Figure3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 41.565217391304344%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/ac18e920778116dbd02a6c47eacef644/59415/Figure3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/ac18e920778116dbd02a6c47eacef644/12f09/Figure3.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/ac18e920778116dbd02a6c47eacef644/e4a3f/Figure3.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/ac18e920778116dbd02a6c47eacef644/59415/Figure3.png 575w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 575px) 100vw, 575px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nFloat house prototype <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>"],"summary":"<p>Amphibious architecture is an adaptation strategy where structures are designed to adapt to flooding.  In this way, a structure is less susceptible to inundation.  Some amphibious buildings are built on elevated foundations. Other buildings are constructed on foundations that under normal circumstances rest firmly on a solid surface. However, during periods of flooding, the building floats. Amphibious buildings with the capacity to float are supported by a buoyancy system that allows the base of a building to move as the water level changes. Therefore, amphibious architecture is ideally suited to flood-prone regions with natural cycles of flooding.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","types":"<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry roof structures</strong> prevent water from entering a building during a flood. These structures incorporate internal or external flood protection barriers <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Wet roof structures</strong> allow floodwaters to flow into and remain in a building during a flood and flow out of the building when the floodwater begins to subside. Wet roof structures are constructed with materials that can withstand flood damage. Hence, wet roof structures are designed to mimic natural landscapes such as floodplains <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Permanent static elevations</strong> are structures that are permanently elevated as an adaptation measure to flooding. They are usually located in areas where flooding occurs regularly <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Buoyant foundations</strong> allow a building to sit on a regular foundation during dry weather but float during a flood. Buoyancy foundations consist of three basic elements, buoyancy blocks that allow the building to float, vertical guideposts that control the movement of the structure up and down, and a subframe that holds the platform and building together <sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup></li>\n</ul>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/summary/"},"html":"<p>Storm surge barriers are heavily engineered movable or fixed barriers/gates that are closed to prevent flooding during bad weather forecasts.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> They are commonly located across the mouth of a tidal inlet or estuaries to control the water level and prevent excessive amounts of  water from entering the estuary.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> Storm surge barriers can be very beneficial for secondary flood protection,  on the landward side of the barrier. For example, storm surge barriers can reduce the maintenance and construction cost of secondary storm protection structures.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> Because these barriers require a high level of engineering feasibility studies and because they incur high construction costs, they can be challenging to implement as a cost-effective adaptation strategy. Additionally, storm surge barriers are more appropriate in areas with tidal lets that can be closed.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> </p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/image2/"},"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 370px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\